docs.text: " lake placid " marks yet another entry in the series of " predator pics " that were a screen staple in the late 1970s ( post- " jaws " ) and were revived recently by the godawful " anaconda . "
docs.label: negative

docs.text: " placid " claims to be a " horror/comedy " -it's directed by the same guy who did " house " -but its attempts at humor are actually less funny than deadpan seriousness of " anaconda . "
docs.label: negative

docs.text: paleontologist kelly scott ( bridget fonda ) is sent up to maine to examine a tooth removed from a body that had been bitten in half on the lake .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: discovering that the tooth belongs to a crocodile ( which shouldn't even be in this hemisphere ) , kelly goes croc-hunting with game warden jack wells ( bill pullman ) and sheriff hank keough ( brendan gleeson ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: they're joined by an unwelcome guest , hector cyr ( oliver platt ) , a scholar who worships crocs and searches all over the world for them .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: along the way , the merry band meets mrs . delores bickerman ( betty white ) , a weird old lady who lives out on the lake .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: you know what to expect from this movie : lots of shots where the camera is the eyes of the predator ( croc cam ) swimming toward someone's dangling legs while " jaws " -like music plays , one character ( hector ) who's obsessed with the croc and stupidly endangers the rest , another character who insists that the predator can't possibly exist .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: unlike its slippery cousin " anaconda , " " lake placid " wants to present its formulaic plot tongue-in-cheek , which is self-defeating .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the result is neither scary nor funny ; it's just tedious .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: while director steve miner has several horror films on his resume ( including two installments of " friday the 13th " and " halloween h20 " ) , screenwriter david kelley ( best known as the creator of tv series like " ally mcbeal " and " chicago hope " ) doesn't seem to have the stomach for a chomp 'em up flick .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the body count is surprisingly low and doesn't include any of the major characters , and most annoyingly kelly and hector insist that they capture the crocodile alive rather than killing it .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: ( " lake placid " manages to have it both ways-i'll let you discover how for yourself ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the croc itself is mostly computer-generated , of course .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: like the snake in " anaconda , " the thirty-foot monster crocodile doesn't seem real ; it moves too quickly and in ways that seem unnatural .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: " lake placid " also offers little explanation for why a giant crocodile is in maine .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: there is a lot of semi-mystical mumbo jumbo about how " we really don't know much about crocodiles . "
docs.label: negative

docs.text: they would have been better off going with something like the urban myth about alligators in the sewers .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: a movie like this doesn't have to offer much of an explanation ( radioactive mutant ?
docs.label: negative

docs.text: creature from outer space ? ) , but it does have to give the audience something to hang their disbelief on .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: pullman and fonda seem to be plodding through the movie on auto-pilot .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: most of the time , they're probably thinking about killing their agents or wondering if making this movie marks the end of their careers .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: platt and white , on the other hand , seem to be giving their best efforts , and they manage to squeeze a few chuckles out of this sorry script .
